{"/service/ndnp/txdn/batch_txdn_icaria_ver01/data/sn86090330/00517175195/1908020801/0430.xml":{"full_text":"Write VatemifeiK\u00df Verse for toe Sm Anatom\u00a9 OgM\u2014Awards \u00a9Sferedl for tore\u00ae besft\nABSOLUTELY FREE\nThe San Antonio Light will\naward a total dt 22 of the\nheat theater seats for the first\neleven correct answers in the\nconcealed word contest which\ncloses Tuesday.\nESTABLISHED 1881\nCARDINAL GIBBONS\nSAYS PROHIBITION IS\nNOT PROPER SOLUTION\nEminent Churchman Would Limit Number of Saloons and\nTake License Away for Offenses Against the Law as a\nMeans of Checking Evils Growing Out of Liquor Traffic.\nNew Orleans. La.. Feb. 8. \u2014Cardinal\nGibbons, who is stopping here, in an\ninterview on prohibition published to\ndav says:\n\u201cI am satisfied it is practically im\npossible to put prohibition into effect\nin anv large community and the best\nmeans therefore to promote temper\nance is to limit the number of saloons\nbv high license. I would be in favor\nof inflicting severe punishment on the\nproprietors of saloons who violated\nLET COUNTRY REST;\nSTOP GHOST DANCE\nJames J. Hill, Railroad Mag\nnate. Gives View of the\nBusiness Outlook.\nNew York. Fen. B.\u2014James Hill\nchairman of the bojrd of the Great\nNorthern railway, is here from St\nPaul and states that the coming sum\nmer will show a decrease in railroad\nearnings over last summer.\n\"I am not so much of an optimist,\u201d\nhe said, \"as to predict that railroad\nearnings this summer will not be be\nlow those of last summer. I am sure\nthat they will be. But there are more\npeople in this country today than ever\nbefore and they are people of fair in\ntelligence. What the country needs\nnow is rest. Let it have rest and let\na stop be put to this ghost dancing\nand everything will work out all right.\n\"Things are quiet enough every\nwhere. but in the northwest we arc\nfeeling it less than in some other\nplaces. We have no large industria\nplants there and the farmers will\nplant as much wheat as ever.\n\"I should say that the percentage\nof idle equipment on the Great North\nern was somewhat less than the per\ncentage reported to be Idle on the\nroads of the country as a whole.\"\nCommenting on the earnings of the\nGreat Northern, which a few days ago\nreported a large increase in gross for\nthe month of January, Mr. Hill said\nthat it had to be borne in mind that\ncomparison was made with the same\nperiod last year when the road was\ngreatly handicapped by an unusually\nsevere winter.\nMr. Hill in reply to questions said\nthat he could not foresee how long\npresent conditions would last.\n\u201cIf I knew.\" he said, \u201cI would be\nglad to tell you\u2019. But I cannot predict\nhow long it will be before things right\nthemselves.\u201d\n\u00a9fee\nGibbons.\nthe law. in the first instance, and in\nthe second instance of a violation I\nwould revoke the license altogether.\n\"In country places I suggest local\nointion as an excellent means for th\u201c\nrepression of intemperence, if in the\njudgment of a majority of the voters\nthe sale of liquor should be entirely\neliminated.\nlike prohibition that are cer\ntain to be violated had best not be\nmade, for incessant violation draw's\ndown upon them disrespect.\"\nNAME AIDES TO\nENTERTAIN THE\nCATTLE OWNERS\nCommittee Is Selected to Plan\nfor the Forthcoming Con\nvention in This City.\nCharles B. Mullaly, president of the\nBusiness Men\u2019s club, at noon today\nannounced the personnel of the com\nmittee on entertainment for the con\nvention of the Texas Cattlemen s as\nsociation. The convention will be\nheld in San Antonio on March 18, 19\nand 20. and it is expected that not\nless than 3000 Lone Star stockmen\nwill be in attendance.\nOtto Koehler is chairman of the\nentertainment committee, the other\nmembers being: J. w. Kokernot. H.\nL. Halff, I. T. Pryor, Henry Boemer,\nI. J. Hart, Fred W. Cook, Otto Wahr\nmund. A. Joske, Edwin Chamberla.n,\nJoseph H. Frost, J. H. Kampmann,\nDr. A. Graves, Sr., W. C. Rigsby, Jake\nWolff, George McQuaid, Nat M.\nWasher. Silva Heimann. H. Bruhn,\nAlbert Steves, John J. Stevens, J. J.\nKing. Victor Hugo, Vories P. Brown,\nJ. H. Kirkpatrick, J. C. Sullivan, B.\nJ. Mauermann, James P. Barclay, J.\nN. Brown, R. L. Ball, C. A. Goeth, J.\nO. Terrel\u2019 and 3am C. Bell.\nThe committee will hold its first\nmeeting at the rooms of the Busi\nness Men\u2019s club next Tuesday after\nnoon at 4:30 o\u2019clock.\nMORSE IN\nEUROPE, ON\nm HOME\nFinancier Lands at Liverpool,\nbut Cable Calls Him\nto U. S.\nSHOWS HE IS UNDER STRAIN\nRefuses to Talk of His Troubles\nor Discuss Plans for the\nFuture.\nLiverpool, Feb. B.\u2014C. W. Morse of\nNew York will leave here for New\nYork on the steamer Etruria. This\nis a complete change in Mr. Morse\u2019s\nplans, caused by The receipt of a ca\nblegram from New Y\u2019ork. Mr. Morse\narrived this morning on the Cam\npania. The message changing his\nplans was received at Queenstown or\nby wireless between Queenstown and\nLiverpool, and when he landed here\ntoday he informed the correspondent\nof the Associated Press that he was\ngoing to return this afternoon instead\nof proceeding to the continent.\nMr. Morse lingered in the cabin\non board the Campania and was tne\nlast saloon passenger to step ashore.\nHis face bore distinct traces of worry\nwhen he finally appeared at the gang\nway, down which he hurried. It was\nevident that he was anxious to es\ncape interviewers, and he hastened\nIn the direction of the baggage room.\nInterrogated regarding his further\nmovements, Mr. Morse showed a de\ncided disinclination to talk of his af\nfairs or plans. He did say, however,\nhe had received a cablegram from\nNew York which decided him to re\nturn home immediately on board the\nEtruria. It had been his intention\nto proceed to the continent to look\nafter certain business matters which\ndemand attention, but the urgency of\nthe cable advices from the other side\ncaused a reversal of his plans.\nMr. Morse declined to discuss in\nany way his financial affairs or pros\npects of getting out of his reported\ndifficulties.\nSON WHO SLEW PARENT\nPLEADS FOR MERCY\nJackson. Ky., Feb. 8. \u2014At noon the\nfuneral of Judge James Hargis, who\nmet death at the hands of his son, took\nnlace in the little family burial ground\non Crown Knob, around which flows\nthe north fork of the Kentucky river.\nThe dead man lay in a casket of stee.\nand mahogany. Nearby are the graves\nof Judge Hargis' three brothers all of\nwhom died of bullet wounds inflicted\nby implacable enemies.\nBeach Hargis, the murderer, was\npermitted to view the body of his\nfather before it was taken from the\nhouse. He was greatly affected and\nfalling upon his knees said:\n\u201cLord have mercy.\u201d He was re\nturned to the gloomy Breathitt county\njail just about the hour the body of\nhis father was being taken from the\nhouse.\nMRS. MORGAN LEAVES\nMrs. J. Pierpont Morgan, wife o'\nthe famous New York financier, left\nfor California this morning on train\nNo. 9 of the Southern Pacific railroad\nto which the Pullman private car \u201cIn\ndependence\" in w\\ich she was travel\ning was attached. Accompanying her\nwere the two women who complete\nher party.\nGAN you WRITE A VALENTINE VERSE?\nCan you write a Valentine verse\u2019\nTry ft. The San Antonio Light will\nmake it worth your while. The Light\nbelieves there is no end of latent\npoetic talent lying dormant in this\nbeautiful city. Here is a proposition\nthat should appeal to every one in\nwhose soul poetic fire slumbers. Here\nis an opportunity to as\nthe premier Valentine verse writer,\nof San Antonio:\nFor the best Valentine verse The\nSan Antonio Light wil pay Two Dol\nlars.\nFJr the next oest verse One Dollar\nwill be paid.\nFor the third best verse the author\nSAN ANTONIO. TEXAS. SATURDAY. FEBRUARY 8. 1908\nDEAD KING\nCONSIGNED\nTD TOMB\nImpressive Funeral Held Over\nBodies of Portuguese Mur\ndered Ruler and His Son.\nTHONGS VISIT THE CAPITAL\nSimple Peasants and Trades\nmen Pay Tribute to Their\nDead Ruler.\nLisbon, Feb. 8. \u2014Funeral services\nover the bodies of King Carlos and\nhis son Luiz, crown prince of Portugal\nwho were shot to death a week ago\ntoday, were held in the church of\nSan Vincento early this afternoon.\nThe ceremonies were simple, but im\npressive, and the final act in the\nbloody tragedy of February 1 was car\nried to a close without any untoward\nincident.\nThe line of the funeral procession\nfrom the royal chapel to the church\nwas crowded by troops, several ad\nditional regiments having been\nbrought into the city for the purpose.\nAll the governments of Europe and\nAmerica were represented by special\nmissions.\nThe streets were thronged with\npeople. They poured in from the\ncountry, from the towns in the pro\nvinces and from nearby cities, some\nby train, some by carriage or by cart\nand many on foot. In the crowd wero\nlarge numbers of simple peasants and\ntradesmen from the provinces who\nneither knew or cared about the po\nlitical strife, but wished only to mourn\ntheir dead leaders.\nCOLQUITT ANNOUNCES\nSpecial to The Light.\nAustin. Tex.. Feb. B\u2014Railroad\nCommissioner Colquitt today gave\nout his announcement as a candidate\nfor re-election. It is very brief and\nthis statement is found therein:\n\u201c\u2018Whatever Intelligence and ability\nI possess I have unstintedly devoted\nto the duties of the office in an ef\nfort to be of good service to the peo\nple of my state.\u201d\nBOMB\u2019S MISSION FAILS\nNew York. Feb. B.\u2014The explosion\nof a bomb, evidently set off by ene\nmies. wrecked the front of the spag\nhetti manufacturing establishment of\nVito Viviano and brother, Italians, ot\nBiddle street, early today. Ten big\nnanes of the glass in the front of the\nbuilding were shattered and the front\nWas otherwise badly damaged.\nTwo holes had been sawed in the\nwoodwork, evidently for the purpose\nof inserting the bombs. The Viviano\nbrothers and families, living on the\nupper floors of the building, were not\ninjured. Vito Viviano asserted he has\nno known enemy and is at a loss to ac\ncount for the explosion.\nMORRIS FUNERAL TOMORROW..\nServices will Be Held at Family\ndome on West Houston Street.\nThe funeral of Mrs. Lydia Morris,\nwho died on February 5, will be held\ntomorrow afternoon at 2 o\u2019clock from\nher late residence, 3304 West Hous\nton street. The services will be\nconducted by Kev. Nolen B. Har\nmon and interment w\u2019ill be made in\nCity cemetery No. 4.\nwill receive Tne san Antonin Light,\ndaily and Sunday, f e; for ne month.\nRemember that brevity is the soul\nof wit, but you may make the verse\ni long or short, as you choose. Also,\nI it is not necessary that the verse\nshall be witty. Make it serious or\nj comic, according to your fancy. There\nmust be many people and many sub\njects that appeal to you as fitting j\n1 topics for valentine verses. Choose I\nI your own subject, call upon your\nMuse and turn out the cleverest, j\nnearest bit of verse you can.\nThe verses will be passed upon by\ncompetent judges.\nAll contribuiior.a must he in the,\nISIS 15 REACHED IN PHONE WAR;\nBOXES ORDERED DDT OF COURT HOUSE\nJAMES J. HILL. WHO DECRIES\nTHE PRESENT AGITATION\nJAMES J. HILL, of the Great Nor\nthern railroad, who in New\nYork today voiced the opinion\nthat the country needs a rest after\nthe agitation concerning corporations\nin general and railroads in particular.\nSAY FINANCIER GATES AND SON HAVE\nFOREVER QUIT SPECULATIVE GAME\nSell Seat in New York Stock Exchange and It Is Believed the\nStreet Will Know Them No More.\nNew York, Feb. 8. \u2014Rumors circu\nlated in Wall street are to the effect\nthat Charles G. Gates, son of John W.\nGates, has sold his seat on the stock\nexchange and that the street would\nno longer know either the elder or\nthe younger Gates. Charles G. Gates\nleft yesterday for what he said would\nLOCAL WEATHER\nr OCAL weather forecast for San\n\u2022J Antonio and vicinity:\nTonight, showers, warmer; Sunday,\nshowers.\nThe minimum temperature for the\n12 hours ending at 8 o'clock In the\nmorning was 54 and the maximum\nwas 68.\nThe velocity of the wind at 8 o'clock\nin the morning was 4 miles an hour.\nThe record or temperatures as ob\nserv\u2019d at the weather office today\nas compared with a year ago, follows:\n1908 1907\n4 a. m 55 38\n6 a. m 55 35\n8 a. m 55 35\n10 a. m 54 48\n12 noon 56 58\n1 p. m 57 62\nThe general report on weather\nthroughout the country will be found\non page six.\noffice of The Light not later than 6\no'clock Friday evening, February 14.\nThe awards will be announced in\nThe San Antonio Licht of Saturday,\nFebruary 15.\nWrite on one side of the paper\nonly.\nSign your name and address In full.\nAddress all Valentine verses,\nwhether delivered personally or sent\nthrough the mall, to \u201cValentine Ed\ntor,\" San Antonio Light.\nDo not delay or your brightest id j a\ni may take flight, never to return, 'f\nJ you are good at Limericks, send in a\nLimerick Valentine verse. If not.\nwrite some other kind of a valentine\nverse. Now get busy.\nis a keen observer of the trend of af\nfairs. He is in dose touch with con\nditions in the northwest and, while\nnot an alarmist, is prone to look the\nsituation squarely in the face.\nbe a long stay in California, and it Is\nbelieved by the brokers in the street\nthat before leaving he severed all\nconnection with the exchange. A seat\non the exchange was sold on Thurs\nday for $53,000, and this is said to\nhave been the dates seat, fsr which\n$51,000 was paid in February, 1901.\nFLEET CLEARS\nFOR NEXT LEG\nOF JOURNEY\nAmerican Battleships Leave\nPunta Arenas for the\nPacific.\nPunta Arenas, Chile (2 a. m.) \u2014The\nAmerican battleships, accompanied by\nthe torpedo flotilla, cleared from the\nharbor at 1 o'clock this morning on\ntheir way through the western half of\nthe strait to the Pacific coast of\nAmerica.\nFrom Punta Arenas the course lies\nsouthward to Cape Forward, the south\nernmost point on the mainland of\nSouth America, From Cape Forward\nthe strait turns and extends 150 miles\nin a northwesterly direction. After\nCtfpe Pillar has been cleared the bat\ntleships\u2019 prows will be turned north\nward and a course laid along the\nChilean coast to a point near Valpa\nraiso, and thence to Callio. Lieuten\nant Cones, of the flotilla or torpedo\nboat destroyers, will part company\nwith the battleships when Smyth\nChannel. 30 miles from the western\nend of Magellan Strait is reached, and\nwill proceed northwestward through\nthis channel. They will follow the in\nside route that will keep the little vea\nseis well protected from heavy weath\ner and which will also shorten the\nvoyage to Talchuanao. the next stop\nping place, 2130 knots from Punta\nArenas.\nMONEY FOR VERSES\nIn observance of St. Valen\n-5 tine\u2019s Day The San Antonio\nLight offers three suitable\nawards for the best Valentine\nverses received up to 6 o\u2019clock\n5 next Friday evening.\nPRICE FIVE CENTS\nCounty Commissioners Take\nSteps to Enforce Recent\nResolution.\nMAY RESULT IN DAMAGE SUIT\nOusted Company Makes No\nMove Except Officials Say\nService Will Be Furnished\nto_Any Person Who Will\nPay for It.\n4* 4* 4* 4* 4* 4* 4* 4* 4* 4* 4* 4* 4* 4*\n\u2022L Resolved, that the Southwest-\n4- ern Telegraph and Telephone\n4* company be and the same is\n4- hereby notified to remove all of -y\nits telephone wires from the\n4- County Court House building\n4- within three days from the re-\n4- ceiot of this notice: further\n4. Resolved, that in the event\n4- said wires are not removed by\n4> said Southwestern Telegraph\n4- and Telephone company within\n4- the time above specified, then\n4. the same shall be removed by\n4. the county, or under its orders.\n\n4\u00ab4*4*4.4*4*\nThat the telephone controversy in\nthe court house will be brought to a\nfocus within the next three days is\nmanifest by the above resolutions\npassed unanimously this morning by\nthe board of county commissioners.\nThe resolutions were presented by\nCounty Judge Shook.\nThe action of the commissioners to\nday was forecasted several days ago\nbv The Light and It is evident that\nthe plan as outlined at that time will\nbe the one carried out by the county\nin the event the Southwestern com\npany does not comply with the order\nof the commissioners. Sheriff Tobin,\nwho has refused to allow the old phone\nto be taken out of his office, it is un\nderstood. will be tendered the long\ndistance booth now on the first floo\u2019\nof the court house. It is also under\nstoood that no attention will be paid\nto Constable Charles Stevens, who\nhas made a request on the South\nwestern company to continue their\nservice in his office and that at the ex\npiration of three days that phone will\nbe removed over his protest It Is\nalso understood that the San Antonio\ncompany has realized the futility of\nremoving the Southwestern phone,\nnow In the office of the clerk of the\ncourt of civil appeals and which Is\npaid for by the state and that the\ncompany will not insist that it be\ntaken out\nWhat shape the fight will take re\nmains to be seen, but as forecasted\nin The Light the tearing out of the\nwires of the Southwestern company\nwill undoubtedly result in a suit for\ninjunction and damage in which the\nSan Antonio Telephone company and\nthe county commissioners and their\nbondsmen will each be held liable. It\nIs contended by well informed attor\nneys that the contention that the\ncommissioners and their bondsmen\nwill not be responsible in the event\nof damage to any company\u2019s property\nabout the court house, is a contention\nwithout ground and that if a judgment\nis secured by the Southwestern com\npany the commissioners and the mea\nwho are on their bonds will unques\ntionably have to foot the bill.\nJudge Shook does not say in bls res\nolution just how the phones of the\nold company are to be removed, but\nit was stated by an official of the\ncounty today that this work would in\nall probability be delegated to the San\nAntonio Telephone company and that\nthe wires of the opposition company\nwould be clipped by the employes of\nthe San Antonio company under direc\ntion of the county commissioners.\nThe very significant statement by\nthe management of the Southwestern\ncompany that that company would en\ndeavor to supply the service to any\nperson or persons desiring it and offer\ning to pay for it. is the only statement\nthat has been given out. It is known\nthat written requests for service have\nbeen made by some of the county of\nficials on the Southwestern Telephone\ncompany and armed with these it is\nverv likely that the company will fee!\njustified in giving the service demand\ned even if it is necessary to carry the\nmatter to the courts.\nThe result of the telephone contro\nversy. once it gets in the courts, will\nhave much bearing on the present\nanti-oass law operative in Texas. It\nis contended by some that If the cour\u2019\nholds the present contract existing be\ntween the county and the San An\ntonfo Telephone company to be legal\nthat there will then be nothing in the\nwav of similar contracts to evade the\nanti-pass law in its other pkases.","height":"26060","width":"20016"}}
